Annotations

ah <- AnnotationHub() %>%
    subset(species == "Mus musculus") %>%
    subset(dataprovider == "Ensembl") %>%
    subset(genome == "GRCm39") %>% # GRCm39 is relative new release 104 is not out yet
    subset(rdataclass == "EnsDb")
ensDb <- ah[["AH89457"]]
grTrans <- transcripts(ensDb)
trLengths <- exonsBy(ensDb, "tx") %>%
  width() %>%
  vapply(sum, integer(1))
mcols(grTrans)$length <- trLengths[names(grTrans)]

Similarly to the Quality Assessment steps, GRanges objects were formed at the gene and transcript levels, to enable estimation of GC content and length for each transcript and gene. GC content and transcript length are available for each transcript, and for gene-level estimates, GC content was taken as the sum of all GC bases divided by the sum of all transcript lengths, effectively averaging across all transcripts. Gene length was defined as the median transcript length.

gcGene <- grTrans %>%
  mcols() %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  dplyr::select(gene_id, tx_id, gc_content, length, tx_name) %>%
  as_tibble() %>%
  group_by(gene_id) %>%
  summarise(
    gc_content = sum(gc_content*length) / sum(length),
    length = ceiling(median(length)),)

grGenes <- genes(ensDb)
mcols(grGenes) %<>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  left_join(gcGene) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  DataFrame()

Count Data

Load the transcript-level counts

transCounts <- list.files("C:/Users/cronos/Box Sync/Desktop/Renal Hypertrophy/CRH_RNAseq/3_salmon_110621",
                          full.names = TRUE) %>%
  catchSalmon()
colnames(transCounts$counts) %<>% 
    basename() 
libSizes <- colSums(transCounts$counts)
minCPM <- 1
minSamples <- 6

dgeList <- transCounts$counts %>%
    as.data.frame() %>%
    rownames_to_column("tx_id_version") %>%
    gather(key = "sample", value = "Count", -tx_id_version) %>%
    dplyr::filter(Count > 0) %>%
    left_join(grTrans[,c("tx_id_version", "gene_id")] %>%
                mcols() %>%
                as.data.frame()) %>%
    group_by(gene_id, sample) %>%
    summarise(Count = sum(Count)) %>%
  dplyr::filter(!is.na(gene_id)) %>%
    spread(sample, Count, fill = 0) %>%
    as.data.frame() %>% 
    column_to_rownames("gene_id")%>%
  .[rowSums(cpm(.) >= minCPM) >= minSamples,] %>%
  DGEList(
    samples = tibble(sample = colnames(.)) %>%
      left_join(samples),
    genes = grGenes[rownames(.)] %>%
      as.data.frame() %>%
      dplyr::select(
        chromosome = seqnames, start, end, 
        gene_id, gene_name, gene_biotype, description, 
        entrezid, gc_content, length)) %>%
  .[!grepl("rRNA", .$genes$gene_biotype),] %>%
  .[!grepl("lncRNA", .$genes$gene_biotype),] %>%
  .[!grepl("pseudogene", .$genes$gene_biotype),] %>%
  calcNormFactors()

Gene-level count data as output by salmon, was loaded and formed into a DGEList object. During this process, genes were removed if:

  • They were not considered as detectable (CPM < 1 in > 30 samples). This translates to > 15 reads assigned a gene in all samples from one or more of the genotype groups
  • The gene_biotype was any type of rRNA.

These filtering steps returned Gene-level counts for 13,158 genes, with total library sizes between 14,853,597 and 24,086,868 reads assigned to genes. It was noted that these library sizes were about 1.5-fold larger than the transcript-level counts used for the QA steps.

## Compare the density distributions before and after filtering
BeforeFilt <- transCounts$counts %>%
cpm(log = TRUE) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = everything(),
    names_to = "sample",
    values_to = "logCPM") %>%
  split(f = .$sample) %>%
  lapply(function(x){
    d <- density(x$logCPM)
    tibble(sample = unique(x$sample),
           x = d$x,y = d$y)}) %>%
  bind_rows() %>%
  left_join(samples) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x, y, colour = group, group = sample)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_colour_manual(values = groupCols) + 
  labs(x = "logCPM", y = "Density", colour = "Group")

AfterFilt<-dgeList %>%
cpm(log = TRUE) %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = everything(),
    names_to = "sample",
    values_to = "logCPM") %>%
  split(f = .$sample) %>%
  lapply(function(x){
    d <- density(x$logCPM)
    tibble(sample = unique(x$sample),
           x = d$x,y = d$y)}) %>%
  bind_rows() %>%
  left_join(samples) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x, y, colour = group, group = sample)) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_colour_manual(values = groupCols) + 
  labs(x = "logCPM", y = "Density", colour = "Group")

Analysis

Initial MDS

MDS: Project a multi-dimensional space preserving the inter-point distances

dgeList %>%
    plotMDS(plot = FALSE, labels=colnames(dgeList)) %>%
    .[c("x", "y")] %>%
    as.data.frame() %>%
    set_rownames(colnames(dgeList)) %>%
  rownames_to_column("sample") %>%
    left_join(dgeList$samples) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x, y, colour = group)) +
    geom_point(aes(shape=as.factor(treatment)),alpha = 0.7, size = 3) +
    geom_text_repel(aes(label = label), size=4.4, show.legend = FALSE) +
      scale_colour_manual(values = groupCols)+
    labs(x = "Dim1", y = "Dim2",
         colour = "Group", shape = "Treatment")

MDS plot showing grouping by donor.

Initial PCA

PCA: Project a multi-dimensional space onto the directions of maximum variability

pca <- dgeList %>%
  cpm(log = TRUE) %>%
  t() %>%
  prcomp() 
pcaVars <- percent_format(0.1)(summary(pca)$importance["Proportion of Variance",])

  as.data.frame() %>%
  rownames_to_column("sample") %>%

   Sham24vsUnx24 = Unx.24hr-Sham.24hr,

   levels = colnames(design))

Estimation of sample weights

The approach taken for DGE analysis was to use voom-precision weights in order to allow for modelling using Normally distributed data. Sample-level weights were estimated as part of this process, with all samples normally being considered as belonging to the same treatment group, to allow more conservative estimates.

v <- voomWithQualityWeights(dgeList, design, plot=FALSE)

Sample weights after voom transformation. The idealised equal weighting of \(w = 1\) is shown as the dashed line.

Means (x-axis) and variances (y-axis) of each gene are plotted to show the dependence between the two before voom is applied to the data (left panel) and how the trend is removed after voom precision weights are applied to the data (right panel)

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
v2 <- voom(dgeList, design, plot=TRUE)
v2fit <-lmFit(v2, design)
e2fit <-eBayes(v2fit)
plotSA(e2fit, main="Final model: Mean-variance trend")

Strict Comparison between groups

tau <- log2(1.1)

For the comparison between groups, a null hypothesis was tested using a range of values, instead of the point value zero, i.e.

\[ H_0: -\tau < \Delta \mu < \tau \\ Vs. \\ H_A: | \Delta \mu | > \tau \]

The default value used in the function treat() is \(\tau = \log_2 1.2\) and for this analysis, \(\tau = \log_2 1.1\) was chosen as a suitable value.

alpha <- 0.05

tfit <- lmFit(v,design) %>% 
  contrasts.fit(contr.matrix) %>%
  treat(lfc = tau)

This gave the number of genes considered as DE between the comparison groups with Bonferroni adjusted P-value < 0.05.

summary(decideTests(tfit))
##        Sham24vsUnx24 Sham48vsUnx48 Sham72vsUnx72 ShamvsUnx Unx24vsUnx48
## Down             697          1767            47      1706         1224
## NotSig         11733          9569         13004      9527        10514
## Up               728          1822           107      1925         1420

## Down           1378         1443           2566           2526              0

## Up             1575         1419           2958           2933              0
##        t24vst48 t24vst72 t48vst72 ShamvsUnx24 ShamvsUnx48 ShamvsUnx72
## Down       2834     3288      985       12321       12276       12252
## NotSig     7254     5961    11257         693         680         687
## Up         3070     3909      916         144         202         219
topTables <- colnames(contr.matrix) %>%
  sapply(function(x){
  topTreat(tfit, coef = x, n = Inf) %>%
      as_tibble() %>%
      rownames_to_column("No.") %>%
      arrange(P.Value) %>% 
      mutate(DE= adj.P.Val < alpha,
             Status = case_when(
      DE ==TRUE & logFC < 0 ~ "Down",
      DE == TRUE & logFC > 0 ~ "Up"),
      Status = ifelse(is.na(Status), "NotSig", Status))}, simplify = FALSE)

Look for common genes between “ShamvsUnx24” & “ShamvsUnx48” & “ShamvsUnx72”

dt<-decideTests(tfit)
de.common <- which(dt[,1]!=0 & dt[,2]!=0 & dt[,3]!=0)
length(de.common)
## [1] 21
head(tfit$genes$gene_id[de.common], n=10)
##  [1] "ENSMUSG00000006517" "ENSMUSG00000010064" "ENSMUSG00000021822"
##  [4] "ENSMUSG00000022012" "ENSMUSG00000022215" "ENSMUSG00000023908"
##  [7] "ENSMUSG00000024640" "ENSMUSG00000026202" "ENSMUSG00000026683"
## [10] "ENSMUSG00000026819"
cpm(dgeList, log=TRUE, prior.count = 3)[tfit$genes$gene_id[de.common],] %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>%
  rownames_to_column("gene_id") %>%
    as_tibble() %>%
    gather(key = "sample", value = "CPM", -gene_id) %>%
    mutate(CPM = CPM + 1) %>%
    left_join(dgeList$samples) %>%
  mutate(treatment = fct_relevel(treatment, "Sham","Unx")) %>%
  mutate(group = fct_relevel(group, "Sham.24hr","Unx.24hr","Sham.48hr","Unx.48hr","Sham.72hr","Unx.72hr")) %>%
    ggplot(aes(group, CPM, fill = treatment)) +
  geom_point() +
    # geom_text_repel(aes(label = time)) +
  stat_boxplot(geom='errorbar', linetype=1, width=0.5)+
    geom_boxplot() +
    facet_wrap(
        ~gene_id, 
        scales = "free_y", 
        labeller = as_labeller(
            structure(dgeList$genes$gene_name, names = dgeList$genes$gene_id)
        )) + scale_fill_manual(values = treatCols) +
    scale_y_log10()  +
    labs(x = "Treatment Group",
         y = "CPM + 1") +
    theme(legend.position = "none",axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90), 
          strip.text = element_text(size= 10, face="bold"))

#Annotation colour for volcano plot
deCols <- c(
  'Up' = rgb(1, 0, 0, 1),
  'Down' = rgb(0, 0, 1, 1),

  `FALSE` = rgb(0.5, 0.5, 0.5, 0.7),
  `TRUE` = rgb(1, 0, 0, 0.7))

lfc=log2(1.1)
names(topTables[1:3]) %>%
  sapply(function(x){
    topTables[[x]] %>%
      bind_rows() %>%
      ggplot(aes(logFC, -log10(P.Value), colour = Status)) +
      geom_point(alpha = 0.4) +
      geom_label_repel(
        aes(label = gene_name), size = 4,

        linetype = 2,

      scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(-4, 4, by = 2))+

Gene Ontology (GO) Enrichment Analysis for Downregulated Genes

sigIDsDN <- names(topTables) %>%
  sapply(function(x){topTables[[x]] %>%
  dplyr::filter(adj.P.Val < 0.05 & Status=="Down") %>%
    extract2("entrezid") %>%
    unlist() %>%
  na.omit() %>%
    unique()
        }, simplify = FALSE)
eGO_DN <- names(sigIDsDN) %>%
        sapply(function(x){
            enrichGO(
                gene = as.character(sigIDsDN[[x]]), 
                # universe = as.character(uv), 
                # ont = "ALL", 
                pAdjustMethod = "fdr",
                pvalueCutoff = 0.05 , 
                OrgDb = orgDb, 
                readable = TRUE) %>% 
            simplify() # This step helps to remove redundant GO terms using semantic similarity
        }, simplify = FALSE)
